</tt><p>
&quot;Mita Hunka&quot; my Brothers of Choice and &quot;Heyatawin&quot; (Anne) Woman-on-the-ridge<br><br>
The Medicine Wheel has four principle directions..East where beginnings occur, South where information is acquired and applied to further our beginnings, West where we introspect to evaluate our application of that information to that which we have undertaken or begun.  And, finally the North where we complete that which was begun.  In success we gain wisdom and in failure, also, we gain wisdom.<br>
The East symbolizes beginnings, the rising sun..the start of a new day..darkness yields to a growing light.  Yellow or Gold is the color that marks the East on the Medicine Wheel, where the Eagle sits.  At any dawning there is much to speculate about as there is with any new beginning.  The far seeing and global view of the Eagle is broad..nonspecific..and conducive to options.  The theme for the East is Illumination.<br>
The South symbolizes new growth, not unlike the coming of spring and its eruption of new life.  A beginning either grows or dies.  Green is the symbolic color and it is the place of the Mouse.  A mouse is one who does not see with the broad vision of his Eagle brother.  He is one who applies close scrutiny...attention to detail..sequential method.  The Mouse is the symbol of Innocence and Trust.  Arrogance born of anger and fear blinds one to learning..innocence opens the path.  Trust allows us to &quot;believe&quot; that which we have learned.  The absence of trust leaves us uncertain...unable to commit...doubting.  It robs us of the ability to continue our beginnings (projects, jobs..relationships..marriage..parenting.)<br>
The West is Black..and the end of a beginning.  The Bear sits here to represent Introspection.  An inward look to truthfully evaluate the chosen plan(s) that led us from beginning to fruition. A very important aspect of wisdom that Silent Warrior respects.  If all has gone well..or we discover short comings and correct them, then we move to the North.<br>
The North, which is White, suggests some purity of thought and process..gained from Innocence and Trust (knowledge) ...properly applied and ultimately evaluated (introspection).  At the North, the seat of Wisdom, sits the White Buffalo...a symbol of the gifts of a good life.<br>
Good Warriors protect the Mouse...if he is killed, the wheel is broken.  Paul is right...we need to protect our children that they may capitalize on innocence and trust.  We must see through the dim, weak eyes of the bear (introspect) that the Mouse within our individual Medicine Wheel is injured.<br>
When a Warrior drops a sacred Eagle feather to the ground, he is forbidden to pick it up.  A Warrior friend must pick it up for him...it is cleansed by Holy Man (lifted to the Creator) and returned to the Warrior who dropped it.  Perhaps it is the same with Innocence and Trust...another Warrior must pick it up for you ..hand it to God, who will give it back to you.<br><br>
I am Tatekohomni Wambli and I own the Earth
